EBS

Root volumes are deleted on termination however you can change this behavior.

EBS volumes are automatically replicated with a single AZ to protect
against hardware failures.

EBS Volume Types

-gp2, gp3 - workloads that require a good balance of performance
and cost effectiveness.

-io1, io2 - provisioned iops - EC2 - hosted relational databases
with high IO demands.

-magnetic - Data archiving and backups. Any large volume
of infrequently accessed data that need to be stored
cost effectively for long term retention.

(Also EBS Multi Attached volumes. Provisioned IOPS EBS volumes
that can attach up to 16 EC2 instances at once. 
ex) shared Filesystems ex) Distributed DBS)

Encryption

- very little perforamnce impact

- The following data types are encypted
    -Data at rest in the volume.
    -Data moving between the volume and EC2
    -Snapshots created from the volume.

-If volume isn't encypted when you create
it. You cannot encrypt it after the fact.

Snapshots
-First one takes the longest. Future ones
don't take that long.

Achieve - allows you to store snapshots
for lower costs if you not need fast
retrieval
    -Recycle bin - Restores accidently deleted
    EBS snapshots

- IOPS - measures # of read and write operations
per second

- Throughput - Measures # of bitsread or written
per second (MB/s)